snippet.textDisplay:
Shakira - That's Shakira referencing the past, not the past predicting the future. As a prediction of the future I give it 0/5.

Simpsons - Ok, that one is even dumber. How is that "predicting corona"? An unrelated type of illnes from a different country. Epidemics existed long before corona. Again, 0/5

Parks and Rec - A team wins the series in the sport they're competing? Wow. Perhaps this is because I don't follow sports but how is that impressive? Is the Cubs an awful team and was their win the biggest fluke imaginable? Either way, at least it can count as a prediction so... 1/5.

Friends - FB might have been the first huge social media platform but smaller ones (like the one Ross is using in this episode) did exist before then. That plotline is about a current technology and not a prediction at all. 0/5.

Jetsons - Video calls? That is one of the most common predictions you'll see in sci-fi movies and shows. It's one of those things pretty much everyone always assumed would happen at some point. 1/5.

Scrubs - That one is ok, but it was more of an edjucated guess. I belive that is something experts at the time theorized. So anyone following the news closley could make the same prediction... and that is also the joke. JD wanted to debate but wasn't prepared to talk to someone who actually knew anything about the subject. 2/5

Back to the Future II - like the video call, a pretty basic thing to predict, and not specific enough to be cool. And it hasn't come true as shown in the movie since almost every game except the kinect still use some sort of controller. Awesome Elijah Wood cameo though. 1/5.

snippet.textDisplay:
"Twice is a coincidence... but after so many times..." etc etc etc NO THAT'S NOT HOW THIS WORKS. If I make 4,503 predictions, and one of them comes true, and then a few weeks later another comes true, and then a few months later another comes true, BUT THERE ARE STILL 4,500 PREDICTIONS THAT HAVEN'T YET COME TRUE, those 3 that did become much less impressive. When you have a show with literally THOUSANDS of events and objects and jokes and b-plots, it would be more remarkable if there weren't a handful of things that became predictions. Put a travel mug on the floor in the middle of a room, with the lid off. Throw a few hundred ping pong balls in the general direction of the mug. Take the mug somewhere where nobody saw what you did, and show them the mug, and let them marvel at how expertly you threw the balls directly into the mug BECAUSE THEY DIDN'T SEE THE HUNDREDS OF BALLS ON THE FLOOR. It's the same thing here, these "predictions" are only impressive if you pretend that the episodes from which they came contained NOTHING else.


To put it another way: take any random sampling of a half-dozen Simpsons episodes. For each episode, make a text file detailing every individual action, event, joke, etc etc etc, that does not reflect a real life event as of the making of that episode. Then, strike off all the things that have happened since the making of that episode (correct "predictions"). Now look at all the things you're left with that didn't happen. "Oh, but those things weren't predictions", and neither were the things that did happen.


This shit is only remarkable if you don't get math. Period.

snippet.textDisplay:
There's an informal logical fallacy called The Texas Sharpshooter. The metaphor is that you fire a gun at a wall, then draw a target around the spot you hit. This is how a lot of so-called psychics claim success, they make a zillion vague predictions, and then when something happens that fits one of them, they want everyone to focus on that and ignore all the predictions that didn't come true.


This is the type of mentality you need to employ in order to think that the Simpsons are especially adept at making predictions. To date, there are over 670 episodes. If you write over 670 short stories about things that haven't actually happened in real life, it's practically inevitable that some of those things you make up are going to happen at some point. It's pretty much a statistical certainty, and it's not impressive or mind-blowing. It's cool, it's neat, it's fun to notice, but don't read too much into it.

snippet.textDisplay:
One of these is a possible prediction: 1. google shakira in red 2. Eric is spot on about how viruses work. 3. I would call it a hopeful guess ( a team winning a sport they play in is not that extrordinary) 4.they were referring to Myspace (created in 2003) which was before facebook 5. the jetsons have what i call the shotgun prediction - its a show about the future with a bunch of guesses of what that future might be like (getting one or two things right out of hundred guesses is not a good prediction) 6. Ben Laden prediction was 5 years in advance (i don't know if he was in Pakistan around the time of that guess). 7. Another shotgun blast ('hands free' is also vague enough to be misinterpreted)
These are always fun episodes because for a moment it is like 'woah' but its important to learn how people 'make predictions' so we can recognize a real one!
